Pege 49. 2. interficiendum curavit: ‘had . . . killed‚' i.e. caused to be killed. See note to p. 39, l. 32. All through this chapter Nepos has confused the facts and the chronology. The death of Heraclides for instance, did not take place until after the banishment of Dion to Leontini and his return, of which Nepos makes no mention.
